{
  "What molecule is considered the primary energy currency used by all living cells to power cellular work?": "",
  "Glucose (a six-carbon sugar broken down during cellular respiration)": "",
  "Cholesterol (a lipid molecule found in cell membranes and hormones)": "",
  "DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid that stores genetic information in cells)": "",
  "ATP (adenosine triphosphate)": "",
  "ATP (adenosine triphosphate) is the universal energy currency of cells. Unlike glucose, which stores large amounts of energy in its covalent bonds, ATP provides small, immediately usable packets of energy (~7.3 kcal/mol per phosphate bond hydrolyzed) that can power virtually every type of cellular work—from muscle contraction to DNA replication to active transport across membranes.": "",
  "What are the three structural components that make up an ATP molecule?": "",
  "Thymine, deoxyribose, and two phosphate groups": "",
  "Adenine, ribose, and three phosphate groups": "",
  "Cytosine, fructose, and four phosphate groups": "",
  "Guanine, glucose, and one phosphate group": "",
  "ATP is a modified nucleotide composed of three parts: (1) adenine, a nitrogenous base; (2) ribose, a five-carbon sugar; and (3) a triphosphate chain of three phosphate groups linked by phosphoanhydride bonds. The 'adenosine' portion (adenine + ribose) is identical to the adenosine found in RNA, while the three phosphate groups distinguish it as a 'triphosphate.'": "",
  "When ATP is hydrolyzed by the enzyme ATPase, what products are formed?": "",
  "Glucose plus oxygen gas as the two main products of the hydrolysis reaction": "",
  "AMP plus two separate inorganic phosphate groups released simultaneously from ATP": "",
  "ADP (adenosine diphosphate) + inorganic phosphate (Pi) + released energy": "",
  "Two ATP molecules formed by splitting the original molecule at the central bond": "",
  "ATP hydrolysis (ATP + H₂O → ADP + Pi + energy) breaks the terminal phosphoanhydride bond between the second and third phosphate groups. This reaction releases approximately 7.3 kcal/mol (30.5 kJ/mol) of free energy under standard conditions, which is coupled to energy-requiring processes. The reaction is catalyzed by ATPases—a large family of enzymes found in every known organism.": "",
  "What type of chemical reaction releases free energy and proceeds spontaneously, having a negative change in Gibbs free energy (ΔG < 0)?": "",
  "Exergonic reaction": "",
  "Neutralization reaction": "",
  "Dehydration synthesis": "",
  "Endergonic reaction": "",
  "Exergonic reactions (Greek: 'exo' = out, 'ergon' = work) release free energy, making ΔG negative. The products contain less free energy than the reactants. Examples include ATP hydrolysis (ΔG = −7.3 kcal/mol), glucose oxidation in cellular respiration (ΔG = −686 kcal/mol), and combustion reactions. Although exergonic reactions are thermodynamically favorable, many still require activation energy to begin.": "",
  "What type of chemical reaction requires an input of free energy and has a positive change in Gibbs free energy (ΔG > 0)?": "",
  "Catabolic reaction": "",
  "Oxidation reaction": "",
  "Endergonic reactions (Greek: 'endo' = within) absorb free energy from their surroundings, making ΔG positive. The products contain more free energy than the reactants. Examples include protein synthesis from amino acids, DNA replication, and photosynthesis's Calvin cycle. In cells, endergonic reactions are driven by coupling them to exergonic reactions—most commonly ATP hydrolysis—through a mechanism called energy coupling.": "",
  "What is the process of adding a phosphate group to a molecule, typically transferring energy from ATP, called?": "",
  "Denaturation": "",
  "Oxidation": "",
  "Hydrolysis": "",
  "Phosphorylation": "",
  "Phosphorylation is the addition of a phosphate group (PO₄³⁻) to a molecule, often catalyzed by enzymes called kinases. When ATP donates its terminal phosphate to a substrate (ATP + substrate → ADP + phosphorylated substrate), the substrate gains potential energy and often changes shape, activating or deactivating its biological function. This mechanism regulates virtually every cellular signaling pathway.": "",
  "Approximately how much free energy is released when the terminal phosphate bond of ATP is hydrolyzed under standard conditions?": "",
  "7.3 kcal/mol (30.5 kJ/mol)": "",
  "100 kcal/mol": "",
  "0.5 kcal/mol": "",
  "686 kcal/mol": "",
  "Under standard biochemical conditions (pH 7, 25°C, 1 M concentrations), ATP hydrolysis releases ΔG° = −7.3 kcal/mol. However, under actual cellular conditions (where ATP, ADP, and Pi concentrations deviate from standard), the actual ΔG can be −12 to −14 kcal/mol—nearly double. The 686 kcal/mol value represents the total free energy released from complete glucose oxidation (C₆H₁₂O₆ → 6CO₂ + 6H₂O), not a single ATP hydrolysis.": "",
  "Why is ATP considered an ideal energy currency for cells rather than directly using glucose for energy?": "",
  "Glucose cannot be broken down by enzymes, so cells have no way to extract its stored energy": "",
  "Glucose is not found in cells because it is only present in the extracellular environment": "",
  "ATP releases small, manageable packets of energy suitable for individual cellular reactions, while glucose contains too much energy to use all at once": "",
  "ATP contains more total energy per molecule than glucose, making it a more concentrated fuel": "",
  "Glucose oxidation releases 686 kcal/mol—far too much energy for a single cellular reaction. Releasing it all at once would generate destructive heat. Instead, cells break glucose down gradually through glycolysis, the citric acid cycle, and oxidative phosphorylation, capturing the energy in ~30–32 ATP molecules. Each ATP then delivers a precise ~7.3 kcal/mol packet, perfectly sized for individual enzymatic reactions.": "",
  "What two major cellular processes regenerate ATP from ADP and inorganic phosphate (Pi)?": "",
  "Diffusion and osmosis": "",
  "Cellular respiration and photophosphorylation": "",
  "Mitosis and meiosis": "",
  "Transcription and translation": "",
  "ATP is continuously recycled through the ATP–ADP cycle. Cellular respiration (in mitochondria) uses energy from oxidizing glucose and other organic fuels to drive ATP synthase, which catalyzes ADP + Pi → ATP (oxidative phosphorylation). In photosynthetic organisms, the light-dependent reactions of photosynthesis also generate ATP via chemiosmosis (photophosphorylation). A human body recycles approximately 40 kg of ATP daily through this cycle.": "",
  "Approximately how much total ATP does the average human body recycle per day, highlighting the enormous turnover rate of this molecule?": "",
  "About 1 gram, since cells use very little ATP for daily metabolic processes": "",
  "About 100 grams, because most energy comes from direct glucose oxidation instead": "",
  "About 40 kg (roughly equal to body weight)": "",
  "About 1,000 kg, far exceeding body weight due to extremely high metabolic demand": "",
  "Despite the body containing only about 250 grams of ATP at any given moment, each ATP molecule is recycled approximately 500–750 times per day. This means the total daily turnover is roughly 40 kg—approximately equal to body weight. During intense exercise, the turnover rate increases dramatically, with muscle cells recycling their entire ATP pool every 1–2 minutes.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'ATP' (adenosine triphosphate)?": "",
  "A double-stranded molecule that stores genetic information": "",
  "A type of protein that catalyzes chemical reactions": "",
  "A lipid bilayer that forms the cell membrane": "",
  "The primary energy-carrying molecule in cells, composed of adenine, ribose, and three phosphate groups": "",
  "ATP (adenosine triphosphate) is a nucleotide consisting of adenine, ribose, and three phosphate groups linked by high-energy phosphoanhydride bonds. It serves as the universal energy currency of cells, providing immediately usable energy for cellular work when its terminal phosphate bond is hydrolyzed (ATP → ADP + Pi). Every known living organism uses ATP as its primary energy-transfer molecule.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'ADP' (adenosine diphosphate)?": "",
  "A nucleic acid found only in the nucleus": "",
  "The lower-energy molecule formed when ATP releases energy by losing its terminal phosphate group": "",
  "An enzyme that breaks down phosphate bonds": "",
  "A high-energy molecule with three phosphate groups": "",
  "ADP (adenosine diphosphate) is the product of ATP hydrolysis, containing adenine, ribose, and two phosphate groups. ADP is the 'spent' form of ATP—like an empty rechargeable battery. It is continuously recycled back to ATP through the addition of a phosphate group (ADP + Pi → ATP), powered by energy from cellular respiration or photophosphorylation. This ATP–ADP cycle is the fundamental energy exchange mechanism in all cells.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the term 'phosphorylation'?": "",
  "The removal of a hydroxyl group from a molecule": "",
  "The condensation of amino acids into a polypeptide chain": "",
  "The splitting of water molecules by light energy": "",
  "The addition of a phosphate group to a molecule, typically transferring energy and altering the molecule's activity": "",
  "Phosphorylation is the covalent attachment of a phosphate group (PO₄³⁻) to a molecule, catalyzed by enzymes called kinases. When ATP donates its terminal phosphate to a target protein or substrate, the recipient molecule changes its conformational shape and functional activity. This mechanism is the most common post-translational modification in cell signaling, regulating enzymes, receptors, ion channels, and transcription factors.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the term 'exergonic reaction'?": "",
  "A reaction that converts light energy into chemical energy": "",
  "A reaction that only occurs at extremely high temperatures": "",
  "A reaction that requires continuous energy input and cannot occur spontaneously": "",
  "A chemical reaction that releases free energy, with products containing less energy than reactants (ΔG < 0)": "",
  "Exergonic reactions have a negative ΔG (change in Gibbs free energy), meaning the products are at a lower energy state than the reactants and the difference is released as usable energy. Examples include ATP hydrolysis (ΔG = −7.3 kcal/mol) and the complete oxidation of glucose (ΔG = −686 kcal/mol). Being thermodynamically favorable does not mean instantaneous—many exergonic reactions still require enzymes to lower the activation energy.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes the term 'endergonic reaction'?": "",
  "A reaction catalyzed exclusively by inorganic catalysts": "",
  "A reaction that releases large amounts of heat to the surroundings": "",
  "A reaction that breaks down complex molecules into simpler ones": "",
  "A chemical reaction that absorbs free energy, with products containing more energy than reactants (ΔG > 0)": "",
  "Endergonic reactions have a positive ΔG, meaning the products store more free energy than the reactants. These reactions are not thermodynamically spontaneous and require an energy input to proceed. In cells, endergonic reactions are driven by coupling them to exergonic reactions (energy coupling), most commonly ATP hydrolysis. Examples include synthesis of macromolecules (proteins, nucleic acids), active transport against concentration gradients, and carbon fixation in the Calvin cycle.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'ATP hydrolysis'?": "",
  "The exergonic cleavage of ATP's terminal phosphate bond by water, releasing ADP, inorganic phosphate, and free energy": "",
  "The splitting of water molecules during photosynthesis": "",
  "The synthesis of ATP from glucose during glycolysis": "",
  "The formation of peptide bonds between amino acids": "",
  "ATP hydrolysis (ATP + H₂O → ADP + Pi + energy) is the reaction that releases the energy stored in ATP for cellular use. The terminal phosphoanhydride bond is cleaved by water in a reaction catalyzed by ATPase enzymes. The ~7.3 kcal/mol of released free energy is not simply dissipated as heat but is mechanically coupled to drive conformational changes in motor proteins, ion pumps, and biosynthetic enzymes.": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'substrate-level phosphorylation'?": "",
  "ATP production driven by a proton gradient across a membrane": "",
  "The phosphorylation of glucose at the start of glycolysis": "",
  "The direct enzymatic transfer of a phosphate group from a phosphorylated substrate molecule to ADP, forming ATP": "",
  "The absorption of phosphate from the soil by plant roots": "",
  "Substrate-level phosphorylation occurs when an enzyme directly transfers a high-energy phosphate group from a substrate molecule to ADP, producing ATP without requiring an electron transport chain or oxygen. This mechanism generates ATP in glycolysis (2 ATP per glucose, catalyzed by phosphoglycerate kinase and pyruvate kinase) and in the citric acid cycle (1 GTP/ATP per cycle, catalyzed by succinyl-CoA synthetase).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'oxidative phosphorylation'?": "",
  "The process of ATP synthesis powered by the energy released from electron transport and the resulting chemiosmotic proton gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane": "",
  "The phosphorylation of proteins by kinase enzymes that regulate signal transduction pathways": "",
  "The oxidation of ATP molecules to release stored energy for powering cellular work processes": "",
  "The direct transfer of phosphate groups between substrate molecules without an electron transport chain": "",
  "Oxidative phosphorylation is the primary ATP-producing pathway in aerobic organisms, generating approximately 26–28 of the 30–32 ATP molecules per glucose. Electrons from NADH and FADH₂ pass through the electron transport chain (Complexes I–IV) on the inner mitochondrial membrane, releasing energy that pumps H⁺ ions into the intermembrane space. The resulting proton-motive force drives ATP synthase (Complex V) to catalyze ADP + Pi → ATP—a process called chemiosmosis, elucidated by Peter Mitchell (1961 Nobel Prize).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes a 'coupled reaction' in biochemistry?": "",
  "A reaction that requires two different enzymes to catalyze the same step": "",
  "A thermodynamically unfavorable (endergonic) reaction driven by linking it to a thermodynamically favorable (exergonic) reaction, typically ATP hydrolysis": "",
  "Two separate reactions occurring in different cells simultaneously": "",
  "The bonding of two identical substrate molecules": "",
  "Energy coupling is the fundamental mechanism by which cells perform thermodynamically unfavorable work. An exergonic reaction (usually ATP hydrolysis, ΔG = −7.3 kcal/mol) is mechanistically linked to an endergonic reaction so that the overall ΔG is negative. For example, the Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase couples ATP hydrolysis (exergonic) to the transport of 3 Na⁺ out and 2 K⁺ in against their concentration gradients (endergonic).": "",
  "Which definition BEST describes 'Gibbs free energy' (G) in biological systems?": "",
  "The thermal energy released as body heat during metabolism": "",
  "The total kinetic energy of all molecules in a cell": "",
  "The portion of a system's energy that is available to perform work at constant temperature and pressure": "",
  "The energy stored exclusively in covalent bonds of DNA": "",
  "Gibbs free energy (G), named after Josiah Willard Gibbs, quantifies the maximum amount of reversible work a system can perform at constant temperature and pressure. The change in free energy (ΔG) determines reaction spontaneity: ΔG < 0 (exergonic, spontaneous), ΔG > 0 (endergonic, non-spontaneous), and ΔG = 0 (equilibrium). In biology, ΔG predicts whether metabolic reactions will release or require energy, making it the central thermodynamic quantity for understanding cellular energetics.": "",
  "During intense muscle contraction, a sprinter's myosin motor proteins undergo repeated power strokes to slide actin filaments. Each power stroke requires the hydrolysis of one ATP molecule. What specific role does ATP hydrolysis play in this mechanical process?": "",
  "ATP hydrolysis causes the myosin head to release from actin and re-cock into the high-energy conformation for the next stroke": "",
  "ATP builds new actin filaments during the sprint": "",
  "ATP hydrolysis destroys the myosin heads after each contraction": "",
  "ATP hydrolysis provides the signal to start running": "",
  "In the cross-bridge cycle, ATP binding causes myosin to release from actin (rigor release). ATP is then hydrolyzed (ATP → ADP + Pi), and the released energy re-cocks the myosin head into a high-energy conformation. When myosin rebinds actin and releases Pi, the power stroke occurs, sliding the thin filament. ADP is then released, and the cycle repeats. Without ATP, myosin remains locked to actin—explaining rigor mortis.": "",
  "A firefly produces bioluminescent flashes to attract mates. The enzyme luciferase catalyzes the oxidation of luciferin, consuming one ATP molecule per flash of light. What type of energy transformation is occurring in this reaction?": "",
  "Light energy → chemical energy stored in ATP": "",
  "Chemical energy → nuclear energy": "",
  "Kinetic energy → potential energy": "",
  "Chemical energy (ATP + luciferin) → light energy (bioluminescence) + heat": "",
  "Firefly bioluminescence demonstrates ATP's versatility beyond mechanical and transport work. Luciferase catalyzes: luciferin + ATP + O₂ → oxyluciferin + AMP + PPi + CO₂ + light (562 nm yellow-green). The reaction has an extraordinary quantum yield of ~88%—meaning 88% of the chemical energy is converted to light rather than heat, making it one of the most efficient light-producing reactions in nature.": "",
  "The sodium-potassium pump (Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase) in a neuron's membrane uses one ATP molecule to transport 3 Na⁺ ions out and 2 K⁺ ions into the cell against their concentration gradients. What type of reaction coupling makes this energetically unfavorable transport possible?": "",
  "The exergonic hydrolysis of ATP is coupled to the endergonic active transport of ions against their gradients": "",
  "The pump creates ATP rather than consuming it": "",
  "The ions diffuse passively and ATP is consumed separately": "",
  "The pump uses osmosis, which requires no energy": "",
  "The Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase is a classic example of energy coupling. ATP hydrolysis (ΔG = −7.3 kcal/mol) phosphorylates the pump, causing a conformational change that moves 3 Na⁺ out and 2 K⁺ in—both against their electrochemical gradients (endergonic). This pump consumes approximately 20–25% of all ATP produced by resting cells and is essential for maintaining the membrane potential (−70 mV) that enables nerve impulse transmission.": "",
  "A marathon runner 'hits the wall' at mile 20, experiencing sudden fatigue, heavy legs, and mental fog. Physiologically, this occurs because glycogen stores are depleted and the rate of ATP regeneration drops sharply. Which energy system was primarily sustaining the runner before the wall, and what happens after?": "",
  "The runner was using anaerobic glycolysis the entire time": "",
  "Photosynthesis was powering the runner; without sunlight, ATP drops": "",
  "The creatine phosphate system was primary; after depletion, the runner switches to fermentation": "",
  "Aerobic oxidative phosphorylation of glycogen was primary; after depletion, the runner relies more heavily on slower fat oxidation, reducing ATP output": "",
  "During sustained aerobic exercise, muscles primarily oxidize glycogen (stored glucose) via oxidative phosphorylation, producing ~30–32 ATP per glucose rapidly. When glycogen is exhausted (~20 miles for most runners), the body shifts to beta-oxidation of fatty acids—which yields more ATP per molecule (e.g., ~106 ATP from palmitate) but at a much slower rate due to complex metabolic processing. The reduced rate of ATP production causes the dramatic fatigue known as 'hitting the wall.'": "",
  "A toxicology student learns that cyanide (CN⁻) binds irreversibly to cytochrome c oxidase (Complex IV) in the mitochondrial electron transport chain. Why is cyanide poisoning so rapidly lethal?": "",
  "Cyanide blocks the final electron acceptor in the ETC, halting electron flow and stopping oxidative phosphorylation—the source of ~90% of cellular ATP production": "",
  "Cyanide prevents glycolysis from occurring by inhibiting the enzyme hexokinase in the cytoplasm": "",
  "Cyanide causes ATP to spontaneously decompose into ADP and phosphate throughout the entire cell": "",
  "Cyanide destroys all ATP molecules already present in the body by cleaving their high-energy bonds": "",
  "Cyanide binds to the iron (Fe³⁺) center of cytochrome c oxidase, preventing it from transferring electrons to O₂ (the final electron acceptor). This blocks the entire electron transport chain, stopping the proton gradient and shutting down ATP synthase. Since oxidative phosphorylation produces ~26–28 of the ~30–32 ATP per glucose (~90%), its cessation is catastrophic. Cells revert to anaerobic glycolysis (only 2 ATP per glucose), which is insufficient for high-energy organs like the brain and heart.": "",
  "In a biochemistry lab, an enzyme catalyzes the synthesis of glutamine from glutamate and ammonia—an endergonic reaction (ΔG = +3.4 kcal/mol). The enzyme only functions when ATP hydrolysis (ΔG = −7.3 kcal/mol) occurs simultaneously. What is the net ΔG of this coupled reaction, and is it spontaneous?": "",
  "0 kcal/mol; at equilibrium": "",
  "−7.3 kcal/mol; only the ATP hydrolysis portion proceeds": "",
  "+10.7 kcal/mol; non-spontaneous": "",
  "−3.9 kcal/mol; spontaneous (the overall reaction is exergonic)": "",
  "When reactions are coupled, their ΔG values are additive: (+3.4) + (−7.3) = −3.9 kcal/mol. The negative net ΔG means the coupled reaction is thermodynamically spontaneous. This is precisely how cells drive unfavorable biosynthetic reactions—glutamine synthetase couples ATP hydrolysis to glutamine synthesis, using the excess free energy from ATP to overcome the energy barrier. This principle applies to thousands of ATP-coupled reactions in cellular metabolism.": "",
  "A student compares substrate-level phosphorylation in glycolysis with oxidative phosphorylation in the electron transport chain. How do these two mechanisms of ATP production differ in terms of yield per glucose molecule?": "",
  "Both produce exactly the same amount of ATP": "",
  "Substrate-level produces ~4 ATP (2 in glycolysis + 2 in citric acid cycle); oxidative phosphorylation produces ~26–28 ATP": "",
  "Substrate-level produces ~30 ATP; oxidative produces ~2 ATP": "",
  "Neither mechanism produces ATP; they only produce NADH": "",
  "Per glucose molecule, substrate-level phosphorylation directly produces 4 ATP: 2 in glycolysis (net) via phosphoglycerate kinase and pyruvate kinase, plus 2 GTP (equivalent to ATP) in the citric acid cycle via succinyl-CoA synthetase. Oxidative phosphorylation, powered by NADH and FADH₂ electrons flowing through the ETC, produces the remaining ~26–28 ATP via chemiosmosis. This makes oxidative phosphorylation responsible for approximately 85–90% of total ATP yield from glucose.": "",
  "A cell biologist observes that a growth factor binding to a receptor triggers a cascade of protein phosphorylation events inside the cell, ultimately activating gene transcription. What type of enzyme transfers phosphate groups from ATP to these signaling proteins?": "",
  "Ligases": "",
  "Protein kinases": "",
  "Helicases": "",
  "Phosphatases": "",
  "Protein kinases are enzymes that catalyze the transfer of the terminal phosphate group from ATP to specific amino acid residues (typically serine, threonine, or tyrosine) on target proteins. The human genome encodes approximately 518 protein kinases (the 'kinome'), which collectively regulate nearly every cellular process. Phosphatases perform the reverse reaction, removing phosphate groups. Together, kinases and phosphatases act as molecular on/off switches in signaling cascades such as the MAP kinase pathway.": "",
  "Peter Mitchell received the 1978 Nobel Prize for proposing the chemiosmotic hypothesis. According to this model, how does ATP synthase in the inner mitochondrial membrane generate ATP?": "",
  "By substrate-level phosphorylation using citric acid cycle intermediates": "",
  "By directly transferring electrons from NADH to ADP": "",
  "By using the proton-motive force (H⁺ gradient) generated by the electron transport chain to drive the rotational catalysis of ADP + Pi → ATP": "",
  "By splitting water molecules and capturing the released energy": "",
  "Chemiosmosis explains how the electron transport chain's energy is converted to ATP. As electrons pass through Complexes I, III, and IV, energy is used to pump H⁺ ions from the mitochondrial matrix into the intermembrane space, creating an electrochemical gradient (proton-motive force). H⁺ ions flow back through ATP synthase (a molecular rotary motor), causing its rotor to spin at ~100 revolutions/second, catalyzing the condensation of ADP + Pi → ATP at a rate of ~3 ATP per full rotation.": "",
  "A sports physiologist explains that during the first 10 seconds of an explosive sprint, muscles primarily use creatine phosphate (CP) to regenerate ATP rather than glycolysis or oxidative phosphorylation. Why is the creatine phosphate system ideal for this brief, intense activity?": "",
  "Creatine phosphate produces more ATP per molecule than any other energy source": "",
  "Creatine phosphate does not require any enzymes to function": "",
  "Creatine phosphate is stored in the bloodstream and delivered to muscles during exercise": "",
  "Creatine phosphate transfers its phosphate directly to ADP in a single, extremely rapid enzymatic step (catalyzed by creatine kinase), regenerating ATP faster than any other pathway": "",
  "The creatine phosphate (phosphocreatine) system is the fastest ATP regeneration pathway because it involves a single enzymatic reaction: CP + ADP → creatine + ATP, catalyzed by creatine kinase. This reaction occurs approximately 10 times faster than glycolysis and produces ATP almost instantaneously. However, CP stores are limited (lasting only ~8–10 seconds of maximal effort), after which muscles must transition to glycolysis (anaerobic) and eventually oxidative phosphorylation (aerobic) for sustained ATP production.": ""
}